--- SeamStress review: sendCriticalAlert() — cosmetic key isolation on a critical-alert email path ---
seam: 001-cosmetic-key-isolation (kind: safety_delivery) from benchmark/entries/001-cosmetic-key-isolation/seam.json

================ RANKED FINDINGS ================

[1] (critical, confidence=high) VERIFIED_REAL
    sendEmail silently swallows ALL failures — 429s and every other error (auth failure, timeout, DNS, 5xx) all return { sent: false } — and sendCriticalAlert responds only with a console.warn, so a critical security alert can be permanently and silently lost.
    reasoning: The catch block in mailer.ts has two arms that are behaviorally identical: status===429 returns { sent: false }, and everything else also returns { sent: false }. No error is ever re-thrown. sendCriticalAlert receives that flag, logs a warning, and returns a resolved promise, so the caller cannot tell delivery failed. This is not merely latent: the CRITICAL_KEY being revoked, a provider outage, a network blip, or an account-level 429 (see finding 2) all reach this path during ordinary operation and produce zero delivery with zero actionable signal. This merges the six critics who described the same swallow-and-warn contract; they agree on both mechanism and severity.
    verdict: verified_real — The catch block in mailer.ts is conclusive: both the 429 branch and the catch-all branch return `{ sent: false }` — no error is ever re-thrown and no distinction is made between a rate-limit and a hard failure (auth error, DNS failure, 5xx, etc.). sendCriticalAlert receives that flag, emits only a console.warn, and returns a resolved promise. The caller has no way to detect or retry a failed delivery. The finding's description of mechanism and severity is fully supported by the source.
      evidence (mailer.ts:43):   } catch (err) {
    const status = (err as { status?: number }).status;
    if (status === 429) return { sent: false };
    return { sent: false };
  }
      evidence (notifications.ts:27):   const result = await sendEmail(CRITICAL_KEY, to, subject, body);
  if (!result.sent) {
    // Best effort: note it and move on.
    console.warn(`[alert] critical alert to ${to} was not delivered`);
  }

[2] (high, confidence=high) JUDGMENT_CALL
    Key isolation is cosmetic: BULK_KEY and CRITICAL_KEY belong to the same provider account (acct_7fb2), so bulk-digest traffic that exhausts account-level rate limits, reputation, or triggers a suspension also blocks the critical key.
    reasoning: config.ts explicitly states both keys are 'issued under the same provider account (account id acct_7fb2)'. Email providers enforce rate limits, sending reputation, spend caps, and suspensions at the account tier, not per API key. sendNightlyDigest loops over tens of thousands of recipients on BULK_KEY; when the account hits its ceiling the provider returns 429s (or worse) for subsequent requests including those on CRITICAL_KEY. The failure is reachable through the ordinary nightly-digest operation, and it feeds directly into finding 1's silent-drop path — so the 'dedicated key' provides dashboard distinguishability, not delivery isolation. Four critics raised this identically; they split on severity (critical vs high). I cap it just below finding 1 because it is the trigger, and its harmful outcome only manifests through finding 1's swallow — but it is genuinely reachable, so it stays high.
    verdict: judgment_call — The finding is real but hinges on provider-specific account-level enforcement behavior that cannot be confirmed from the source alone. The code explicitly documents that both keys share account 'acct_7fb2', and the comment states the split is purely for 'dashboard distinguishability' — confirming the cosmetic-isolation claim. The nightly digest loop over 'tens of thousands' of recipients on BULK_KEY is described in comments. The silent-drop path in sendCriticalAlert is confirmed: any non-200 response (including a hypothetical account-level 429 on CRITICAL_KEY) yields { sent: false } and only a console.warn. However, whether account-level rate limits actually bleed across API keys depends entirely on the specific provider's enforcement model — some providers do isolate per-key, others enforce at the account tier. The code and comments cannot prove that claim; it is an architectural assumption about external provider behavior. The risk is real and plausible given shared-account design, but the severity hinges on a context a human (or provider documentation) must confirm.
      evidence (config.ts:7): // Bulk and critical email were split onto two API keys so the two traffic
// streams are distinguishable in the provider dashboard. Both keys are issued
// under the same provider account (account id "acct_7fb2").
export const BULK_KEY = requireEnv("MAIL_BULK_KEY");
export const CRITICAL_KEY = requireEnv("MAIL_CRITICAL_KEY");
export const PROVIDER_ACCOUNT = "acct_7fb2";
