[3] (medium, confidence=high) VERIFIED_REAL
    The 'MUST reach the recipient' contract has no enforcement: no retry, no backoff, no fallback channel, no dead-letter queue, and no durable failure record — a single transient failure produces permanent non-delivery.
    reasoning: sendCriticalAlert makes exactly one attempt and, on { sent: false }, emits a console.warn and returns void. There is no retry loop, no secondary channel (SMS/push/backup SMTP), and no persisted record an operator could reconcile. This is distinct from finding 1: even if error signaling were fixed, the path would still lack durability and recovery. It is largely an architectural/design gap — the harm requires a failure to first occur (which findings 1 and 2 make reachable), and the missing infrastructure is a 'harden this' concern rather than a specific bad input, so it caps at medium. Two critics raised it; consolidated here.
    verdict: verified_real — The code directly confirms the finding. The function is explicitly documented as one that 'MUST reach the recipient', yet makes exactly one send attempt, catches all failures (including non-429 errors, which also return { sent: false }), and on failure only emits a console.warn before returning void. There is no retry loop, no fallback channel, no persistence of the failure, and no mechanism for operator reconciliation. The comment 'Best effort: note it and move on' directly contradicts the stated MUST-deliver contract.
      evidence (notifications.ts:27): export async function sendCriticalAlert(to: string, subject: string, body: string): Promise<void> {
  const result = await sendEmail(CRITICAL_KEY, to, subject, body);
  if (!result.sent) {
    // Best effort: note it and move on.
    console.warn(`[alert] critical alert to ${to} was not delivered`);
  }
}
