================ SYNTHESIS ================
The audit consolidates to three distinct issues on the critical-alert path. The most consequential is that sendEmail collapses every failure — 429s, auth errors, timeouts, 5xx — into a silent { sent: false }, so an alert that 'MUST reach the recipient' is dropped with only an ephemeral warn log. The shared-account structure defeats the intended key isolation, and the key-isolation itself is unenforced by convention. Failures are reachable via ordinary bulk traffic; the retry/durability gap is a real but architectural design shortfall.

